Document: Converting GLSL to Godot Shaders
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/converting_glsl_to_godot_shaders.rst
Summary: This document explains how to convert GLSL shaders to Godot's shader language, highlighting key differences and providing conversion examples.

Godot Shader Language is based on GLSL, but it has some differences. This tutorial will cover the most common differences and how to convert them.

Built-in Variables
-----------------

Godot Shaders have a set of built-in variables that are not present in GLSL. These variables are used to access information about the current rendering context, such as the camera, light, and material properties.

Here are some of the most common built-in variables:

*   `TIME`: The current time in seconds.
*   `UV`: The texture coordinates of the current fragment.
*   `VERTEX`: The vertex position in model space.
*   `NORMAL`: The normal vector in model space.
*   `COLOR`: The vertex color.
*   `MODELVIEW_MATRIX`: The model-view matrix.
*   `PROJECTION_MATRIX`: The projection matrix.
*   `WORLD_MATRIX`: The world matrix.
*   `VIEW_MATRIX`: The view matrix.
*   `MODEL_MATRIX`: The model matrix.
*   `NORMAL_MATRIX`: The normal matrix.
*   `CAMERA_MATRIX`: The camera matrix.
*   `VERTEX_COLOR`: The vertex color.
*   `UV2`: The second set of texture coordinates.
*   `ALPHA`: The alpha value of the current fragment.
*   `SCREEN_UV`: The screen-space UV coordinates.
*   `SCREEN_TEXTURE`: The screen texture.
*   `DEPTH_TEXTURE`: The depth texture.
*   `NORMAL_TEXTURE`: The normal texture.
*   `ROUGHNESS`: The roughness value.
*   `METALLIC`: The metallic value.
*   `EMISSION`: The emission value.
*   `TRANSMISSION`: The transmission value.
*   `CLEARCOAT`: The clearcoat value.
*   `SUBSURFACE`: The subsurface value.
*   `AMBIENT_LIGHT_COLOR`: The ambient light color.
*   `LIGHT_COLOR`: The light color.
*   `LIGHT_DIRECTION`: The light direction.
*   `LIGHT_ATTENUATION`: The light attenuation.
*   `LIGHT_SPECULAR`: The light specular.
*   `LIGHT_TYPE`: The light type.
*   `LIGHT_COUNT`: The number of lights.
*   `LIGHT_POSITION`: The light position.
*   `LIGHT_SPOT_EXPONENT`: The light spot exponent.
*   `LIGHT_SPOT_CUTOFF`: The light spot cutoff.
*   `LIGHT_LINEAR_ATTENUATION`: The light linear attenuation.
*   `LIGHT_QUADRATIC_ATTENUATION`: The light quadratic attenuation.
*   `LIGHT_QUADRATIC_ATTENUATION`: The light quadratic attenuation.
*   `LIGHT_QUADRATIC_ATTENUATION`: The light quadratic attenuation.
